text_answer.content:
Vocabulary sentences 3, 4, and 5 can all be watershed, pivotal, and unprecedented. They don't mean the exact same things, but they're all related to similar situations, so the nuance between them will be difficult. I'd also say the vocab is a little easy for 12th grade.
Feels a little easy for 12th grade.
Soft yes on bias, mostly because mentioning anti-vaccination movements is... tricky. It's one of those things where the teacher doesn't know the politics of the student or their family, so while it's accurate information, we might be stepping into an issue without realizing.
On a related note, this passage feels broad and unfocused. Phrases like "created unprecedented opportunities for international cooperation in disease prevention" don't really say anything meaningful. How did they create these opportunities? What opportunities were they? What diseases were prevented? Realistically there are only two initiatives specifically mentioned: the quarantined ships during the Black Death and the initiation of public health campaigns for vaccination programs. There are plenty of other developments and initiatives out there which could add specificity. I was expecting a deeper discussion on germ theory. Washing hands and sterilization techniques could also be discussed along with complications like super bugs that develop when antibiotic regimens aren't completed.  The way this passage is written and the topic it's supposed to be about just feels... incomplete.
Key Details 1 and the Analyzing Information questions both talk about quarantines as the earliest form of public health intervention.

For the inference, the main idea of the last paragraph is basically choice A, so not an inference. Since I do feel this passage needs a pretty substantial overhaul, I'm going to skip suggesting an alternative.

text_answer.content:
For the false or unverified information, paragraph 4 seems to contradict previous statistics. Specifically that, overall, there's going to be a 2.1% job decline according to paragraph 2. On a purely surface level, said job decline suggests there will be a human worker surplus, not a shortage. Unfortunately, in order to prove that both statements can be true, the passage needs to get into the weeds a little and I'm not sure it has the space/time.
Side note: it's now 2025. The 1.5 million statistic reads as predictive, but it's for 2022. It either needs to state that there was a 1.5 million human worker shortage in 2022 (and adjust the implications) or it needs to forecast a similar statistic for sometime in the actual future (2030 or 2035). My suggestion is the former option, since the later will give the passage a shelf life.
All three Key Details questions are statistics focused.

For the inference question, "The ability to work in tandem with new technologies while providing critical and creative thinking that machines cannot replicate is becoming a crucial differentiator in the job market."
B is close, but the passage does spend some time talking about fields where technology is unlikely to have as much of an effect, making B is too broad.
I'm going to skip giving a suggestion on this one. Nothing is specifically jumping out at me, and I do feel this passage needs enough of a revision that suggesting an inference might be meaningless.

text_answer.content:
The passage states that dogs evolved from gray wolves at the end of paragraph 1, which isn't true. Rather, dogs and gray wolves share a common (now extinct) ancestor.
The answers for key Details question 1 don't actually answer the question. It's looking for the evidence which suggests the timeline, not the timeline itself.
For the key idea, B is too broad. There's not discussion of how the domestication of dogs has shaped humanity over thousands of years. E is a better answer. Although it doesn't include other instances of domestication, like cats or horses, those were a part of the concluding paragraph and can be reasonably overlooked when it comes to the main idea.
Key Details question 2 and the Analyzing Information questions focus on the same detail.

For the inference question, answer C is not a reasonable inference. It suggests a cause and effect relationship that requires far too much intention behind domestication than can reasonably be inferred from the passage as written. It is a reasonable assumption and would make for a fantastic hypothesis for further research, but it's not an inference.
An alternative: "The evolution of dogs as they are today was originally unintentional." This is supported by the mention that humans inadvertently selected wolves who displayed less aggression and greater sociability.

Neither prompt is great. 1 is just a compare and contrast and refers to a topic that isn't fully explored (cats). 2 requires students to make assumptions about the risks of selective breeding - it's also a highly controversial topic.
Alternatives:
"In three or four sentences, describe the steps which allowed humans to domesticate dogs." - It's a fancy way of asking students to summarize paragraph 2, but they'll have to fill in some gaps as well.
"Which domesticated animal is your favorite? Compare that animal to its wild cousins and describe the favorable traits they share." - This might need to be cleaned up a little, but the basic idea is to let the student choose a domesticated animal (pets, farm animals, or whatever) and examine what about those animals might have attracted human attention to begin with - such as the hunting, protection, and empathy described for dogs. Obviously dogs are the easy answer here, but it's open ended enough that even choosing canines will force students to think through their answer.

text_answer.content:
Vocabulary question 3 and 4 are interchangeable. Even the passage conflates the pituitary and hypothalamus, giving no indication of what each does individually.
Vocabulary sentence 5 is about as borderline as we can get on the topic, but I'd still say it's a no go.
Key Details question 1 is obviously C because it is the most detailed answer. It's only the only answer that isn't an absolute. 2 is obviously B for similar reasons.
Key Details question 2 and Analyzing Information are about the same topic.

For the inference, answer A is basically the main idea of the concluding paragraph and is especially summed up in the last sentence. The explanation also say B is wrong, though it's directly supported by the passage in paragraph 2.
Another possible inference is "Animals besides humans engage with music in a different, less impactful way." This is supported by the sentence "Scientific research has revealed that our brains are uniquely wired to process and respond to musical stimuli..."
